---
import Layout from '../layouts/AboutLayout.astro';

import Image from '../components/mdxComponents/Image.astro';
import Link from '../components/mdxComponents/Link.astro';
import CareerTimeline from '../components/CareerTimeline.astro';
import ToSinglePost from '../components/mdxComponents/ToSinglePost.astro';
import Button from '../components/Button.astro';
import { proseClasses } from '../utils/proseClasses';
---

<Layout
	title="Curious, Multidisciplinary Designer"
	description="Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet"
>
    <section class={`${proseClasses} mx-auto`}>
      <p>I started building before I knew what design was.</p>  

<p>In school, while others were memorizing formulas, I was opening up Blogspot templates and pulling them apart. I didn’t know the word “UX.” I didn’t know there were people whose careers revolved around interaction and systems. I only knew that if I changed a few lines of HTML, the page transformed. A sidebar disappeared. A header shifted. Colors obeyed. It felt close to magic — not mystical, but procedural. You typed something. The world responded.</p>

<p>That early instinct wasn’t about aesthetics. It was about control and cause. If something felt off, I wanted to understand why. If something didn’t exist, I wanted to see if I could make it exist. Static sites, Jekyll experiments, broken layouts that took hours to debug — they were less about building websites and more about learning how systems behave. Looking back, that was design thinking before I had language for it.</p>

<p>Years later, in large-scale mobile games, the same curiosity resurfaced — just at a different resolution. Instead of sidebars and headers, I was looking at retention curves and progression loops. Why does a player return on day seven but not day three? Why does a small feedback delay reduce completion rates? In environments where millions of interactions compound daily, weak assumptions surface quickly. I became less interested in isolated screens and more interested in incentives, clarity, and momentum. Design, to me, became the architecture of behavior over time.</p>

<p>Building remained constant. I prototype not because I need to ship production code, but because thinking sharpens when it meets constraints. HTML, CSS, JavaScript, SwiftUI — they are tools to shorten the distance between idea and evidence. And now, AI sits alongside them. Not as a replacement for judgment, but as an accelerator of curiosity. It allows me to test more variants, simulate more systems, question more defaults. Software has always felt like a wand — something that turns intention into reality. The difference today is speed. The responsibility, however, remains the same: to build systems that are thoughtful, intentional, and worth interacting with.</p>
          </section>

</Layout>
